metadata.title: Cessna 182 Skylane
aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 182 Skylane Model Certification and Features
The 182T/T182T Skylane was certified on 23 February 2001.
The 182T/T182T Skylane is an improved version of the 182S.
The 182T/T182T Skylane was introduced in 2001.
The 182T/T182T Skylane features a redesigned cowling.
The 182T/T182T Skylane features redesigned wheel fairings.
The 182T/T182T Skylane includes a 12V power port.
The 182T/T182T Skylane has a smaller gear strut step.
The T182T Skylane is powered by a turbocharged and fuel-injected Lycoming TIO-540-AK1A piston engine.
The Lycoming TIO-540-AK1A engine produces 235 hp (175 kW).
The T182T Skylane includes a 4-place oxygen system.
The T182T Skylane has improvements for high altitude flight.
The optional "Nav III" avionics package was introduced for the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2004.
An optional leather interior was introduced for the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2004.
Redesigned wingtips were introduced for the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2005.
New landing lights were introduced for the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2005.
Optional AmSafe inflatable restraints were introduced for the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2005.
AmSafe inflatable restraints became standard in the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2009.
The Garmin G1000 instrument system became standard in the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2007.
Multiple optional additional avionics packages were introduced for the 182T/T182T Skylane in 2007.
941 units of a Cessna 182 Skylane model were built.
A Cessna 182 Skylane model was certified on 3 October 1996.

text:
Certified on 3 October 1996.  941 built.
182T/T182T Skylane
Improved 182S introduced in 2001 with a redesigned cowling and wheel fairings, 12V power port, a smaller gear strut step, and other improvements.  The T182T is powered by a turbocharged and fuel-injected 235 hp (175 kW) Lycoming TIO-540-AK1A piston engine, a 4-place oxygen system, and other improvements for high altitude flight.  2004 saw the introduction of the optional "Nav III" avionics package and an optional leather interior.  2005 introduced redesigned wingtips, new landing lights, and optional AmSafe inflatable restraints (which became standard in 2009).  2007 introduced the Garmin G1000 instrument system as standard, as well as multiple optional additional avionics packages.  Certified on 23 February 2001.
